    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1913-02-24T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1913-02-24T00:00:00-05:00" n="1700"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1700">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 367.11/131.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Ambassador</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 429.]</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Constantinople</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1913-02-24">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 24, 1913</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Referring to the Embassy’s despatch No. 374 of
                    the 31st ultimo, in regard to requisitions made by the Ottoman authorities for
                    war purposes, I have the honor to enclose herewith a copy, with translation, of
                    a note verbale identique on this subject sent recently to the Sublime Porte by
                    the diplomatic missions in this city.</p>
                <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">W. W. Rockhill</hi>.</signed>
                </closer>
                <pb facs="1446" n="1342" xml:id="pg_1342"/>
                <frus:attachment>
                    <opener>
                        <seg rendition="#center">[Inclosure—Identic note verbale.]</seg>
                    </opener>
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Embassy</gloss> to the
                                <gloss type="to">Ministry for Foreign Affairs</gloss>.</hi>
                    </head>
                    <opener>
                        <dateline rendition="#right">
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                                <hi rend="italic">Constantinople</hi>
                            </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1913-02-22">
                                <hi rend="italic">February 22, 1913</hi>.</date>
                        </dateline>
                    </opener>
                    <p>The Embassy of the United States of America regrets being unable to agree
                        with the point of view expressed by the Imperial Ministry in its note
                        verbale dated January 30 last, on the subject of the requisition for war
                        purposes of horses and vehicles belonging to foreign subjects.</p>
                    <p>The principal object of the communications which the Embassy has had the
                        honor to address to the Imperial Ministry on the question was to assure in
                        these proceedings, in so far as they concern its nationals and under the
                        reserves formulated, the guaranties of a general sort established by the
                        treaties and by custom.</p>
                    <p>Every sort of requisition, as well as the appraisement for the purpose of
                        offering the interested party a fair compensation, can therefore take place
                        only with the presence of a consular delegate.</p>
                    <p>It naturally remains understood that the payment for objects requisitioned
                        should be arranged at the very time of the requisition, either in money or
                        by draft accepted by the Imperial Ottoman Bank.</p>
                </frus:attachment>
            </div>
